	<h2>What Causes Tinnitus?</h2>
	<p>
		Tinnitus can develop for many different reasons, and part of finding
		meaningful relief starts with understanding what may be contributing to
		your symptoms.
	</p>
	<p>
		For many people, tinnitus is closely linked to hearing loss. When the brain
		receives less sound input than it's used to, it can try to compensate by
		"turning up the gain," which may be perceived as ringing, buzzing, or other
		phantom sounds.
	</p>
	<p>
		Noise exposure is another common cause. Over time, repeated exposure to
		loud sounds can damage the delicate structures of the inner ear and lead to
		tinnitus.
	</p>
	<p>
		Sometimes the cause is more straightforward, such as earwax buildup, which
		can press against the eardrum and result in fullness, muffled hearing, or
		ringing sensations.
	</p>
	<p>
		A variety of medical conditions can also play a role, including TMJ
		disorders, high blood pressure, sinus problems, or ear infections. In other
		cases, tinnitus may be related to medications, as certain prescriptions
		list ringing in the ears as a potential side effect.
	</p>
	<p>
		Because there are so many possible causes, tinnitus is rarely
		one-size-fits-all. A professional evaluation is the best way to identify
		what may be driving your symptoms and determine the most appropriate next
		steps for relief.
	</p>

	<h2>Types of Tinnitus</h2>
	<p>
		Tinnitus is commonly defined as the perception of sound in the absence of
		an external source; however, it is a complex symptom with several distinct
		presentations. Classifying tinnitus can be helpful in identifying potential
		underlying causes and guiding appropriate management.
	</p>

	<h3>Pulsatile Tinnitus</h3>
	<p>
		Pulsatile tinnitus is characterized by a rhythmic pulsing or whooshing
		sound that often aligns with the individual's heartbeat. It is frequently
		associated with changes in blood flow, vascular abnormalities near the ear,
		or muscular activity.
	</p>

	<h3>Non-Pulsatile Tinnitus</h3>
	<p>
		Non-pulsatile tinnitus is the more common presentation and typically
		manifests as a continuous sound such as ringing, buzzing, humming, or
		hissing. This form is most often associated with changes or damage within
		the auditory system, particularly the cochlea or auditory nerve.
	</p>

	<h3>Subjective Tinnitus</h3>
	<p>
		Subjective tinnitus is the most prevalent type and can only be heard by the
		individual experiencing it. The perception of sound may vary significantly
		in pitch, intensity, and quality between individuals. In most cases,
		subjective tinnitus is considered a symptom rather than a standalone
		condition and is often linked to underlying auditory or neurological
		changes.
	</p>

	<h3>Objective Tinnitus</h3>
	<p>
		Objective tinnitus is rare and differs in that it can be heard by both the
		individual and an external examiner. It is typically associated with
		identifiable physical or vascular sources, such as middle ear
		abnormalities, blood vessel disorders, or muscle spasms that generate
		audible internal sound.
	</p>
	<p>
		Understanding the different classifications of tinnitus can assist in
		identifying potential underlying causes and supports a more individualized
		approach to evaluation, treatment, and management.
	</p>

	<h2>Tinnitus Evaluations at Commonwealth Audiology</h2>
	<p>
		Our tinnitus evaluations are designed to be comprehensive, allowing us to
		fully understand your symptoms, potential underlying causes, duration, and
		the situations in which your tinnitus is most bothersome, as well as its
		impact on your daily life.
	</p>
	<p>During the evaluation, our audiologist may:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			Review your medical history and discuss potential contributing factors
			or triggers
		</li>
		<li>
			Examine your ears for cerumen (wax) buildup, irritation, or any physical
			obstructions
		</li>
		<li>
			Perform a comprehensive hearing assessment to evaluate auditory function
			and cochlear sensitivity
		</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		This thorough assessment helps us identify possible contributing factors
		and develop a personalized management plan aimed at reducing the impact
		tinnitus has on your quality of life.
	</p>

	<h2>Tinnitus Management and Treatment Options</h2>
	<p>
		While there is no single "cure" for tinnitus, there are many reliable ways
		to reduce its impact and improve your quality of life. Your treatment plan
		will be tailored specifically to you.
	</p>

	<h3>Lifestyle Adjustments</h3>
	<p>
		Small changes can support better tinnitus management, such as protecting
		your ears in loud environments, reducing caffeine or alcohol, staying
		active, maintaining healthy sleep habits and practicing stress-reducing
		techniques like deep breathing, meditation or yoga.
	</p>

	<h3>Sound Therapy</h3>
	<p>
		Soft background noise can help reduce your awareness of tinnitus. Options
		may include white noise generators, nature sounds, or music. Additional
		devices to consider are ear level maskers with built-in sound generators or
		smart phones with tinnitus specific apps can provide relief.
	</p>

	<h3>Hearing Aids</h3>
	<p>
		For many people, tinnitus accompanies hearing loss. When hearing aids
		amplify everyday sounds, the brain shifts focus away from internal sound,
		making symptoms less intrusive. Many modern devices include dedicated
		tinnitus features for added support.
	</p>

	<h3>Stress Management &amp; Counseling</h3>
	<p>
		Stress can make tinnitus feel sharper or louder. Relaxation techniques,
		such as mindfulness, breathing exercises, and Cognitive Behavioral Therapy
		(CBT), can help reduce its emotional impact and improve coping.
	</p>
	<p>
		Effective treatment will vary between patients based on several factors
		including the cause and severity of tinnitus. While working with an
		audiologist, it is crucial to determine the most suitable treatment plan.
		Appropriate therapies will be recommended and tailored to specific needs in
		order to successfully manage tinnitus and improve quality of life.
	</p>

	<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Tinnitus</h2>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Will tinnitus go away on its own?">
			<p>
				In some situations, it can. If your tinnitus is related to something
				temporary, like a recent loud noise exposure, sinus congestion, or
				earwax buildup, you may notice it fades once the underlying issue
				improves. If the ringing has been present for more than a few weeks
				or is starting to affect your focus, sleep, or daily comfort, it's a
				good idea to have it checked. An audiologist can help identify what's
				contributing and guide you toward meaningful relief.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can stress make tinnitus worse?">
			<p>
				Yes, it often can. Many people notice their tinnitus becomes more
				noticeable during stressful or anxious times. The good news is that
				as stress levels decrease, tinnitus often feels less intrusive and
				easier to manage.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Is tinnitus always caused by hearing loss?">
			<p>
				Not always. While tinnitus and hearing loss commonly occur together,
				many people with tinnitus have completely normal hearing. A full
				hearing evaluation helps us better understand what may be
				contributing in your specific case.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Do hearing aids help with tinnitus?">
			<p>
				For many people, yes. Hearing aids can make tinnitus less noticeable
				by restoring the sounds you've been missing in your environment. Many
				devices also include built-in tinnitus management features designed
				specifically for added relief.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can earwax be the reason for my tinnitus?">
			<p>
				It absolutely can. When earwax builds up, it can block sound from
				reaching the eardrum and sometimes create feelings of fullness or
				ringing. In many cases, safe removal by an audiologist leads to
				noticeable improvement fairly quickly.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

